	(1890,1832,'ENU0151',104,1,'','Fantasy Literature',4104,'','','H',3,56,'',1,'3','N',0,'1','',0,'','204',NULL,'7-9',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,5,50,3,'This course, first of all, orients students into various representative modern fantasy writers (Sade, Hoffmann, Poe, Lovecraft, Wells, Kafka, Le Guin, Gibson, Oates and Gaiman) and its generic characteristics such as metamorphosis, existential and structural uncertainty, alternative spatio-temporal experiences, and so on. Psychoanalytic perspectives are introduced and, later, applied to textual analysis. Reading materials include five short stories and two novels, which cover various sub genres of fantasy (the Gothic, horror, the grotesque, and utopia) and are analytically, critically accessed by way of lectures and discussions with a view to not only psychological but also social and political aspects.',0,24,24,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1891,1833,'ENU0176',104,1,'','Introduction to Literary Theory',4094,'','','H',3,56,'',0,'3','N',0,'1','',0,'','305',NULL,'6-8',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,3,50,3,'Objectives This course introduces to students various modes of modern theory including Marxism, psychoanalysis, postmodernism and postcolonialism. Besides a comprehensive historical survey of these theories, students will be required to read, discuss, and critique some representative theoretical texts in detail and to develop accurate, critical understanding of such essential concepts as reification, ideological interpellation, the unconscious, the ego-superego-id structure, drive, Panopticon, simulacrum, to name only a few. Some cinematic and literary texts will be analyzed in light of these theoretical concepts.',0,29,29,0,3,0,0,0,0),
	(1892,1834,'ENU0177',104,1,'','Asian American Literature',4095,'','','H',3,56,'',0,'3','N',0,'1','',0,'','302',NULL,'6-8',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,6,50,3,'This course is designed for story-telling, story-reading, and story-sharing. We\'ll read and discuss stories that have emerged in-between \"Asia\" and \"America\" out of the trans-Pacific flows of people, cultures, politics, and histories since the second half of the nineteenth century. By reading and discussing stories of immigrants, migrants, exiles, travelers, students, cultural mediators, etc., we will understand Asian Americans\' engagement with and intervention into the construction of Asia, America, and the Pacific history and humanities. We\'ll read selections from novels, short stories, poetry, watch films (documentaries and feature-lengths), enjoy music, and think creatively, with our topics of concerns ranging from race, gender, ethnicity, language, identity, human rights, to life politics. In view of the hybrid ethnic and historical constitutions of \"Asian America,\" in the 2013 Fall semester we will study mainly Chinese American and Japanese American stories to make our discussion focused and systematic. Besides, participants are encouraged to reflect on their own experiences of living and learning between Asia and Euro-America as English majors in Taiwan. This course aims to raise participants\' interest and understanding in important issues of cultural exchange, self and other, identity and power, and nation and ethnicity. Participants are encouraged to share their reading and learning experiences. Requirements include group assignments, discussions, presentations, and two short (3-5 pages) response papers. ----2013 3-5',0,4,4,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1893,1835,'ENU0199',104,1,'','Urban Literature',4105,'','','H',3,56,'',1,'3','N',0,'1','',0,'','303',NULL,'6-8',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,5,50,3,'This course highlights the interaction between urban space and the representations of urban specificities in the context of postmodern/postcolonial discourses. It is designed to help students better understand such concepts as the city, space, and the flneur. It is hoped that through a perusal of critical theories and in-depth textual practice, students have a thorough grasp of important issues in urban studies. The course organization will include three interrelated parts. First, we will begin with perusing critical discourses concerning the concept of the city, the configuration of space in the city, and the role the flneur plays in the formation of urban landscape. Secondly, the course will include a theoretical application of the above discourses to several novels and films. We will discuss the relations among urban narratives, cultural production, and representation. It is hoped that through a training of dialectical thinking, students can understand how the representations of urban lives and cultural production reflect off the heterogeneous spaces overlooked as well as how the urban representation provides a site of ideological wrestling. Thirdly, students are also required to study a set of significant key terms often encountered in urban studies. Equipped with a sound knowledge of urban studies, students are expected to synthesize the three parts and explore the interaction between urban narratives and contemporary cultural products.',0,24,24,0,4,0,0,0,0),
