	(1935,1583,'ENM1051',104,1,'','Contemporary Literary Theory & Cultural Studies',4117,'','','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','',NULL,'2-4',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,5,50,3,'The purpose of this course is to introduce students to a range of texts from the fields of literary theory and cultural studies. Besides offering them some methodological co-ordinates for their own future research and training them in techniques of discussing and writing clearly about complex ideas, the course is designed to stimulate students\' critical thinking. In particular, it is hoped that they will learn to reflect sceptically on the dominant cultural values of their own society and educational culture as a result of their close reading of essays and other works that bring into focus some of the most egregious products of stupefaction issuing from the west.',0,10,10,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1936,1584,'ENM1057',104,1,'','English Writing and Research Methods (I)',4118,'','','H',2,57,'',1,'','N',0,'','',0,'','',NULL,'3-4',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,0,50,2,'The course is designed to enable students the following background knowledge and professional skills: (1) To introduce the learners to the concept of \' research\'; (2) To enable them to understand the stages of research; (3) To familiarize the learners to the procedures involved in research; (4) To introduce them to the conventions of research papers; (5) To familiarize them the techniques and conventions of research documentation.',0,7,7,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1937,1586,'ENM2002',104,1,'','Phonology',4119,'','','H',3,57,'',0,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','',NULL,'6-8',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,2,50,3,'This course introduces students to some modern phonological theories and their applications to phonology. Students are required to read the class materials beforehand, to participate actively in the class discussion, and to present a publishable research paper by the end of the semester. Upon completing the course, students should have knowledge of the phonological concepts and the ability to implement the knowledge for phonological data analysis.',0,17,17,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1938,1587,'ENM2019',104,1,'','Statistics and Experimental Design',4120,'','','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','506',NULL,'7-9',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,5,50,3,'On completion of this course, participants will have: -- developed a critical awareness and understanding of elementary-intermediate statistical knowledge to carry out their independent research project at postgraduate level.',0,17,17,0,5,0,0,0,0),
	(1939,1588,'ENM2027',104,1,'','Research Methods and Academic Writing',4121,'','','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'','',0,'','',NULL,'2-4',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,0,50,3,'This course aims to help students develop the ability to compose a well-organized and well-focused academic essay in English. Its goals are to introduce strategies for the purpose, organization, presentation, development, coherence, and unity of thesis writing. Essential elements in a thesis such as summaries, abstracts, arguments, data commentaries, critiques, etc. will be discussed and practice in writing will be assigned. Whenever appropriate, we will also talk about skills in doing independent academic research in language and linguistics. Students are expected to learn to use library resources and explore various approaches of data collection and analysis. The ultimate purpose is to familiarize students with the steps in doing academic research and help them develop abilities in critical thinking/writing, intellectual reasoning, problem-solving, and collaborative learning.',0,12,12,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1940,1589,'ENM3028',104,1,'','Research Methods and Academic Writing (I)',4122,'','','H',2,57,'',1,'','N',0,'','',0,'','',NULL,'3-4',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,1,50,2,'The purpose of this course is to help graduate students improve their academic writing in English and provide them an overview of research-related issues. The class will first introduce the language used in academic writing, followed by the different sections commonly seen in a research paper. Students are expected to lead class discussions, give presentations and write parts of a research paper. The class is designed based on the premise of a constructivist approach. Students are expected to learn by actual doing, exploring actively on their own and constructing their individual understanding and knowledge. The class also aims for foster collaboration and discussions. Based on these, lectures are cut down to minimum. Each student will be evaluated by their progress made in this class.',0,15,15,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1941,1590,'ENC1001',104,1,'','Studies in Shakespeare',4123,'','8','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','',NULL,'7-9',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,5,50,3,'1. In this course, we are going to study a dozen Shakespearean plays, adaptations, and related scholarly articles. 2. Our major textbook is: Stephen Greenblatt, ed., The Norton Shakespeare, Based on the Oxford Edition. New York: Norton, 1997. 3. A detailed schedule is to be discussed and decided after orientation in the first week. It will normally be announced in the class in the second week of the term.',0,11,11,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1942,1591,'ENC1011',104,1,'','Major 20th-Century American Authors',4124,'','8','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','',NULL,'3-5',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,3,50,3,'In Major American Writers of the 20th century, students will study a wide range of fiction from 1930 to the present. The course traces the formal and thematic developments of the novel in this period, focusing on the relationship between writers and readers, the conditions of publishing, innovations in the novel`s form, fiction`s engagement with history, and the changing place of literature in American culture. The reading list includes works by Flannery O`Connor, William Faulkner, Saul Bellow, John Updike, Marilynne Robinson, and Cormac McCarthy, as well as a packet of theoretical and critical readings put together by the instructor.',0,10,10,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1943,1592,'ENC1065',104,1,'','19th-Century English Novel',4125,'','8','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','',NULL,'3-5',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,3,50,3,' As the Victorian period is arguably the most complex, rapidly-changing and replete with the myriad of social problems and conflicts, such as gender, education, social welfare, poverty, industrialization, and crime, among others, the Victorian fiction reflects many social dimensions. We hope to explore broadly and also in depth the representative novels of some major writers, such as Charles Dickens, Rudyard Kipling, Sir Arthur Conan Doyle, Wilkie Collins, and Joseph Conrad. This \"Nineteenth-Century Novels\" course hopes to focus particularly on several major issues: British imperialism, London cosmopolitanism, crime and industrialization, urbanity, modernity, the genre of Gothic and Detective Fiction, the transition between Victorianism and Modernism. The issue of transition between Victorianism and Modernism is fascinating. Some perceive Victorian fiction as forerunner of Modern fiction. For instance, Raymond Williams argues, that since industrialization and urbanization feature modernity, the dating of British Modernism should start from the Victorian period. For him, the Victorian period was the beginning of modernism and modernity, and Charles Dickens should be considered as a forerunner of Modernist fiction. Another major modernist writer, Joseph Conrad, often conceived as the father of Modern fiction, with his complex narratives, actually wrote and published some of his early novels in the late nineteenth century, such as Almayer\'s Folly in 1895, An Outcast of the Islands, 1896; \"An Outpost of Progress,\" 1897; and Heart of Darkness, 1899. Hence, we will reconsider the issue when Victorianism ends and when Modernism starts. In the nineteenth century, especially during the Victorian reign, the imperial conflict between China and the British Empire, and two colonial military expeditions to China incurred by the Opium trade play a large part in the period. Hence, one of the major issues we intend to explore in this course is the representation of China and opium in the Victorian fiction, especially in the novels by the Oscar Wilde, Charles Dickens, Wilkie Collins, and Sir Arthur Conan Doyle. We will also explore the issues of London cosmopolitanism, as London being the epicenter of the British Empire. We will investigate the connection between London as the capital of the British Empire and its peripherals and colonies, especially India and China. Opium smoking in London seems to play a significant part in late Victorian writing. Some of the novels by Dickens, Collins and Wilde in our reading list depict the opium dens in London\'s East End, while Kipling\'s stories depict the opium factory in India.',0,7,7,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1944,3324,'ENC1097',104,1,'','Race and Cultural Representation',4126,'','8','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','',NULL,'2-4',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,5,50,3,'I have many thoughts regarding my teaching philosophy. Some of them can be summarized as follows: I try to give my work as a teacher all the energy, inquisitiveness, enjoyment, commitment , and preparation I can muster. I expect students to work diligently. I will look into the selected texts from an Afrocentric perspective and we will explore the opportunities to study the following authors in the light of a modern philosophy, i.e. Afrocentric methodology developed for the study and analysis of African American discourse. The ten steps I have developed will be utilized in this course to explore the dimensions and contours of a methodological approach to Harlem Renaissance literature and literary genres. My pedagogy depends heavily on dialogue and thus responses to the texts. No student\'s grade has ever suffered because the student disagrees with me. Yet, we must all recognize the difference between intellectual competence and political opinion. Since our subject matter stimulates emotions and challenges the master narrative, we shall work through difficult issues as an enlightened group.',0,17,17,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1945,1594,'ENC2008',104,1,'','Comparative Study of Chinese Syntax and English Syntax',4127,'','8','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','',NULL,'6-8',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,2,50,3,'This course is intended to explore the workings of Universal Grammar by comparing the syntax of Chinese and the syntax of English (as well as other languages when necessary). Important topics in syntax will be discussed by covering both classical and up-to-date works. With the goal to enhance the understanding of Universal Grammar, this course will benefit not only students who are interested in syntactic theory, Chinese and English syntax, but also those working on interfaces between syntax and other linguistic areas (such as sentence processing, L1 or L2 acquisition, etc.).',0,5,5,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1946,1595,'ENC2010',104,1,'','Comparartive Study of Mandarin Syntax and Taiwanese Syntax',4128,'','8','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','',NULL,'2-4',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,2,50,3,'This course will focus on the comparison between Mandarin and Southern Min syntax in three major areas: negation and question, word order, and noun phrases. Since it will be couched in Chomsky\'s Principles and Parameters theory (1981), several meetings in the beginning of the course will be devoted into the discussion of the framework and the significance of such an approach for dialectal studies. They will be followed by the discussion of the papers related to the three areas. Students who are not familiar with the theoretical framework are strongly encouraged to prepare themselves by studying it.',0,1,1,0,0,0,0,0,0),
