	(1948,1597,'ENC2014',104,1,'','Studies in Semantics',4130,'','8','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','',NULL,'2-4',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,3,50,3,'Studies in Syntax is designed as an introduction to contemporary work in syntactic theory. The framework that we will be discussing in class is Chomsky\'s Minimalist Program. By the end of the course, students should be able to understand the main ideas behind the theory (especially with respect to how it differs from its predecessor - Government & Binding) and also to read and analyze Minimalist articles critically. The course is designed as a mixture of lectures, student presentations, and in-class discussions. Please do the readings in a timely manner in order to be able to follow and participate in these discussions. A term paper/squib (8-10 pages, double-spaced) is due at the end of the semester. Students have to choose one or more papers in consultation with the teacher and provide a critical summary, ideally also presenting original data that supports or provides evidence against the analysis in the article.',0,4,4,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1949,1598,'ENC2026',104,1,'','Sociolinguistics',4131,'','8','H',3,57,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','',NULL,'7-9',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,0,50,3,'Course Description This course provides an overview of the field of sociolinguistics, the study of language in its social and cultural contexts. It considers variations of language (in a broad sense) and the socio-cultural factors associated with variations. Among the questions posed in the course are these: How and why do speakers select among the range of linguistic varieties in their repertoire, one language or another, standard or vernacular, regional-sounding or not, formal or casual, gendered in one way or another, and so on? How can such variation be accounted for in a theory of language and society? What kind of knowledge is involved in knowing how to participate in conversations, and how do conversational styles differ from group to group? What are the effects of multilingualism and language contact, for speakers, for communities, and for languages? How and why do standard varieties of languages come to be? Throughout the course, we will learn a variety of theoretical and methodological approaches to the investigation of sociolinguistic data. We will also gain first-hand experience in data collection and analysis through project assignments. Students are highly encouraged to apply sociolinguistic theories and findings discussed in class to communities with which they have personal experiences.',0,33,33,0,0,0,0,0,0),
