	(1956,1553,'END2033',104,1,'','Seminar on Phonetics',4138,'','','H',3,58,'',0,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','',NULL,'2-4',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,3,50,3,'Goals: This is a doctoral-level seminar on phonetics. The goals of this seminar are: 1) to introduce the fundamental aspects of acoustic phonetics and speech perception as a human cognitive mechanism; 2) to introduce various methods and techniques for phonetic experiments; 3) to discuss the current issues in the fields of phonetics and speech perception; 4) to comprehend and investigate the speech perception models; 5) to help students develop their own research proposal and experiment. The ultimate goal for you is to deepen your knowledge of phonetics and speech perception and to heighten your skills for conducting experiments to the level of professional research. You will be required to carefully design and conduct an experiment including developing research questions to test your hypotheses, analyzing the data by using a statistical tool, and interpreting and discussing the results by referring to the current theories. You will be required to write an abstract of your research and be strongly encouraged to submit it to important, prestigious conferences in the field to make a good contribution to the linguistic society as an independent researcher. Here are suggested conferences that you might want to consider: 1. 2009 Annual meeting of Linguistic Society of America (LSA): January 8-11, 2009, Portland, Oregon. This is the biggest international linguistic conference in North America. Usually the abstract deadline is the beginning of September. (http://www.lsadc.org/info/meet-futuremeet.cfm) 2. 156th meeting of Acoustical Society of America (ASA): November 10-14, 2008, Miami, Florida. This conference focuses on various areas of acoustic research involved in not only human speech production and perception, but also animal communication, sound and music, underwater acoustics, etc. (http://asa.aip.org/meetings.html) The abstract deadline is TBA. The good thing about this conference is that all members of ASA can present their research in poster presentation form and that we can meet with phoneticians and engineers from all over the world. General organization of the course: The course will be divided into four parts: basics of acoustic phonetics, basics of speech perception, experimental design and basics of statistics, and speech perception models. There is no required textbook for the course. Mostly we will read articles and book chapters, grasp the main ideas and important concepts, and discuss them in class. You will be responsible for finishing reading assignments before class and being ready for discussion in class. You are welcome to find articles that interest you and bring them in class to read and discuss as a group.',0,4,4,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1957,1554,'END3005',104,1,'','Seminar in Reading Research',4139,'','','H',3,58,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','',NULL,'7-9',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,1,50,3,'This course aims at helping students become familiar with reading theories, research, and practices in L1 and L2. Students will review existing reading research extensively and critically to formulate research/teaching ideas as well as develop research skills and teaching philosophy in reading. We will review research on how children learn to read, how adults read in their first language, and how second language learners read in a second language. A reading packet, which includes articles on different reading models, various types of reading studies, and different instructional approaches, will be compiled as the core text for this course. There are three parts in this reading packet, including L1 reading processes and models, reading in L2, and instruction and assessment issues in L2 reading. We will read, analyze, and discuss a couple of articles per week. Lectures will be kept to the minimum. Your discussion on the issues presented in the reading materials will be the major activity in class. For the midterm project, you will submit a critique of one of the studies read. For the final project, a proposal for a reading research design should be presented orally and submitted in writing. You are also expected to attend graduate lecture series or conference sessions related to ELT and reading. Final grades will be assigned based on the following criteria: Participation & presentation of articles: 30%, Midterm project 30%, Final project 40%.',0,5,5,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(1958,2531,'ENU0150',104,1,'','Introduction to TEFL',4140,'','','H',2,59,'',0,'','N',0,'','',0,'','305',NULL,'6-7',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,0,50,2,'Course Description: This is a one emester, 2 credit, mandatory course for English majors. The main objective of this course is to introduce you to theories and methods of teaching English to speakers of other languages. In this course, we will trace the historical development of second language teaching methods from grammar based curricula to present day interactive methods, where most of our focus will be placed. TESOL approaches and methods will be studied in their practical settings and in terms of their theoretical underpinnings. In addition to the theoretical focus, we will also discuss the practical aspects of teaching English as a foreign/second language. By the end of the course, you will be well-versed in applying major teaching methods that are currently being used in most EFL/ESL classrooms. teaching.',0,23,23,0,1,0,0,0,0),
