	(2526,2666,'ESC0136',104,1,'','Advanced Astronomical Observations',4529,'','8','H',3,92,'',0,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','413',NULL,'7-9',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,5,50,3,'Advanced Observational Astronomy is a (required) course designed for graduate students (in both Astronomy M.S. and Ph.D. programs) who wish to have astronomy as their career. The aim is to equip students with most commonly needed observational techniques and essential observational knowledge so they can understand modern day astronomical observations, and/or conduct their own observations necessary for thesis studies while in school and for independent researches in the future. Because of the wide scope of the course and constrained by limited class hours, Advanced Observational Astronomy will spend most of its time on Spherical Astronomy (including spherical trigonometry, celestial sphere, coordinate systems and time), Photometry, Telescopes and Optics, and if time allows, on Optical Detectors and on Multi wavelength Observations. [Because of the unique nature of radio observation and its importance in Taiwan\'s astronomy, observational theories, instruments and techniques in radio wavelength will be covered by another graduate course Radio Astronomy.]',0,3,3,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(2527,2667,'ESC0137',104,1,'','Interstellar Medium',4530,'','8','H',3,92,'',1,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','413',NULL,'3-5',0,'It\'s designed for graduate students, and too difficult for undergraduate students.',NULL,20,0.4,15,50,3,'The space between the stars in a galaxy is not empty space. There exists gas in ionic, atomic, and molecular form, dust, and cosmic rays. In astronomy, they are called the interstellar medium (or ISM). Studying about ISM is important because of its role between stellar and galactic scales: Stars form within the densest regions of the ISM, molecular clouds, and return the matter and energy into the ISM through planetary nebulae, stellar winds, and supernovae. This interplay between stars and the ISM helps us to determine the life of stars, and galaxies.',0,6,6,0,0,0,0,0,0),
