	(3408,1382,'CLC0017',104,1,'','Language, Culture, and Congnition',5089,'','8','H',3,142,'',0,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','1002',NULL,'7-9',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,0,50,3,'People in different cultures tend to perceive and conceptualize the world differently. Are these differences random or systematic? Can language as part of culture explain some of these differences? What is the relationship between language and mind (or thought)? This course invites you to delve into these fascinating issues and gain some understanding of how our thoughts are shaped by our culture and language. This course expects the students to',0,29,29,0,0,0,0,0,0),
	(3409,1383,'CLC0022',104,1,'','Psycholinguistics',5090,'','8','H',3,142,'',0,'','N',0,'1','',0,'','1003',NULL,'7-9',0,'',NULL,20,0.4,0,50,3,'How do people acquire, comprehend and acquire their first language and what learning mechanisms and psychological processes underlie these behaviors? We will explore the basic linguistic principles and theory, and their interaction with learning mechanisms and psychological processes in language acquisition, comprehension, and production. This course serves as both an introduction course to the field and review of major studies to more advanced issues in Psycholinguistics which function as a milestone to understand what psychological processes and learning mechanism that are common for both first language learners and second language learners and to understand what difference between native speakers and second language learners.',0,14,14,0,0,0,0,0,0),
